on-arrival: hindenburg_hitler_r += 1

The prospect of personal command over the country’s agriculture and economy is enticing to Hugenberg, who aims to eliminate all forms of <span style="color: #c00000;">socialism</span>, restructure Germany’s economy into a heavily capitalistic and laissez-faire system, and transfer power to an elite few. The offer proves too great for Hugenberg to maintain his stance. Franz Seldte of the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**Stahlhelm**</span> is now also confirmed as the next Labor Minister.

Papen has refrained from mentioning to Hugenberg [+ nsdap_leader +]’s demand for new elections, where the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> would have a decisive advantage over his own [? if dnvp_ideology == "Radical": <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>?][? if dnvp_ideology == "Moderate": <span style="color: #003755;">**DNF**</span>?]. However, despite Hugenberg’s willingness to join the cabinet, <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**Stahlhelm**</span> leader Theodor Duesterberg leads a group of prominent conservatives to vehemently oppose that step, and urge that he only support another Papen cabinet instead.

However, as is all too common, [+ nsdap_leader +] is underestimated once more. Hugenberg responds, "We’ll box Hitler in," and, "In two months we’ll have pushed Hitler so far into a corner that he’ll squeal." When another conservative warned that [+ nsdap_leader +] sought a dictatorship, Papen dismissively replied, "You’re mistaken. We’ve hired him!"

