= Negotiations, Pt. 4

Hindenburg and his son have suspected the worst of Schleicher and didn’t take the trouble to investigate the rumors. Taking advantage of this atmosphere of crisis, Papen finally secured Hindenburg’s agreement that tomorrow morning, he is to swear in a new cabinet headed by [+ nsdap_chancellor +].

Hindenburg has approved the ministers proposed, but Papen, knowing that Hindenburg will never make [+ nsdap_chancellor +] the chancellor of a presidential cabinet, purposefully avoids disclosing that detail to him—though he knows Hindenburg will realize it soon enough.

By leaving the Justice Ministry vacant on the list of cabinet members, Papen sought to create the impression that it was being reserved for a <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span> member, and that its appointment was pending final negotiations. This simple act of deception has convinced Hindenburg that he is appointing a parliamentary chancellor, with the [? if not stegerwald_path: Catholic?][? if stegerwald_path: Christian?] party’s earlier overtures lending credence to the scheme.

