= Negotiations, Pt. 4

That evening, Papen once again asked Hindenburg to appoint [+ nsdap_chancellor +] as Chancellor—preferably before Schleicher faces an embarrassing defeat in the Reichstag. However, Hindenburg feels no urgency to remove Schleicher so soon.

Hindenburg has since approved the proposed ministers, but Papen, fully aware that the President would never accept [+ nsdap_chancellor +] as the head of a presidential cabinet, deliberately withholds that detail—though he knows Hindenburg will realize it soon enough.

By leaving the Justice Ministry vacant on the cabinet list, Papen creates the illusion that the post is being reserved for a <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span> member and that final negotiations are still ongoing. This simple act of deception convinces Hindenburg that he is appointing a parliamentary Chancellor, with the [? if not stegerwald_path: Catholic?][? if stegerwald_path: Christian?] party’s earlier overtures lending credibility to the ruse.